This is a no-markup-markup document, sporting the following cool features:

()	labled display line at level 0
	unlabeled display lines at level 0
	more unlabeled display lines at level 0
()	labeled display lines at level 0

[]	Bullet lists:

	here preceded by a text block at level 1, whose (lack of) linebreaks are not respected.

	()	preceded by labeled display lines at level 1
		preceded by unlabeled display line at level 1, whose (lack of) linebreaks are respected.

	-	Here is one bullet item.

			unlabled display line at level 2, whose (lack of) linebreaks are respected.

	-	Here is another one.

		but this is interpreted as a text block at level 2, whose (lack of) linebreaks are not respected.

	this is interpreted as a text block at level 1, whose (lack of) linebreaks are not respected.

In fact, here are some more unlabled display lines:

	this one
	and this one
()	followed by a labeled one
	followed by an unlabeled one
()	labeled with name		DSP:some_name

[]	Numbered lists with labels that are either

	[]	automatic, or

	[*]	custom.

	Furthermore, each item can be *named* and *referred to*:

	[]	ITM:x
		The named item can be referred to anywhere in the document.

	[]	ITM:y
		When referring to [ITM:x] above, any common initial path shared between the location of the referring expression and the location of its referent will be omitted. The same applies with respect to [ITM:z] below.

	[**]	ITM:z
		Of course, items with custom labels can also be named!

Due to the feature mentioned in [ITM:y], a reference to [ITM:x] or [ITM:z] occurring elsewhere may appear differently.

[]	ITM:one
	Displayed lines of text suitable for mathematical equations, which are either

		unlabeled
	()	automatically labeled (and named),	DSP:one
	(+)	custom labeled (and named), or,		DSP:two
		unlike [DSP:one] above, unlabeled.

It can even end with

	unlabled display block

